cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The play was fine on this hand. Nothing extra to talk about. However, the bidding is another matter. First let's see if Lisa should make a game try (which is what 3H is). Let's count her Bergen Declarer Points. She has 14 HCP plus 1 length point for 15 starting points. Once Roberta raises spades, she can do some declarer addons--1 for the 4 card heart side suit, and 1 for the 2 doubletons--that gives her 17. Playing Bergen evaluation, you need 26 points for game. So, if Roberta is at the top of her range, they have enough points for game. Therefore, Lisa's bid is reasonable, but optional.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On the plus side, she has all "prime" high cards, meaning Aces and Kings. On the minus side, she has reasonably flat distribution (no singletons or voids). In general, for thin games, you should strongly prefer to have unbalanced distribution. Nevertheless, a game try is certainly not out of the question with Lisa's hand, just a tad optimistic.|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, what about Roberta? Let's count her dummy points. She has 8 Starting points. Once Lisa bids 1S she can count 1 for her club doubleton--that is 9 Dummy Points. Her 3@D bid shows 7-9 which puts her at the top of her range. Therefore, she should accept Lisa's invitation, as her hand is as good as it gets and bid 4@S. Her hand doesn't look so hot in general. But once you limit yourself to 7-9, it is at the top of the range. Now, having said that, although 4S makes, it actually is not a very good game. 4S depends on a lot of good things happening. |
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Here, you have 3 sure losers--2 hearts and a club. That means you cannot lose anything else. Therefore: 
a) you need the CA onside, b) You need the Q of spades to be singleton or doubleton and, and c) you need hearts to split 3-2. If you showed me those 2 hands and asked if I wanted to be in 4 spades, I would answer emphatically not. As it is probably less than 20% that it makes. This was a case where Bergen evaluation was a bit optimistic.|
