NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the lead,  Ann has a tough problem. Generally, it is a bad idea to lead a suit the opponents have bid. And Marge did bid spades, and Ginny implicitly bid hearts by bidding Stayman and bidding 3N over 3S. So, I do not fault Ann for not leading a major. However, I think, because her diamonds are better than her clubs, she should lead a diamond. As it turns out, the best lead is a major, particularly a spade, so it did not really matter but I recommend leading your best unbid suit always against NT. |
PG| ***** 159 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Z@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One other subtle point. If there is a good chance that opener only has 4 cards in a bid major and you hold 2 honors in that major, especially if you have a 5 card suit sometimes, despite my rule of not leading the opponents suit, a lead of that suit works well. Had Ann had a 5th spade, a low spade could very well work out. But if you stick to my rule about not leading the opponents suit, and leading your best remaining suit, you will do best in the long run. I would not worry about that subtlety I just talked about. Just thought it was interesting, and you might make note of it for future hands to see when it works out.|
